diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can damage any part of the body, including skin, joints, and/or organs inside the body.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can develop as a complication of inadequately treated strep throat or scarlet fever, affecting the heart, joints, skin, and brain.

diagnoses.name: Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection spread by ticks, characterized by a rash, fever, headache, and muscle pain.

diagnoses.name: Infectious mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Commonly known as mono, caused by the Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), symptoms may include fever, swollen lymph nodes, sore throat, and rash.

diagnoses.name: Hepatitis B
diagnoses.description: A severe liver infection caused by the hepatitis B virus (HBV) that can become chronic and lead to liver failure, cancer, or cirrhosis.

diagnoses.name: Leptospirosis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial disease that affects humans and animals, caused by the bacteria Leptospira. Symptoms can range from mild to severe, including fever, rash, and kidney damage.

diagnoses.name: Dengue Fever
diagnoses.description: A mosquito-borne illness found in tropical and sub-tropical climates worldwide, causing high fever, rash, severe headache, and pain behind the eyes.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. It primarily affects children. The symptoms include fever, rash, swelling of the hands and feet, irritation and redness of the eyes, swollen lymph glands in the neck, and irritation and inflammation of the mouth, lips, and throat.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet Fever
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease resulting from a group A streptococcus infection, known for a characteristic rash.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein Purpura
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that causes rash, abdominal pain, and joint inflammation. It's more common in children.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones. Can lead to metabolic issues, including affecting fertility, and has been associated with periodontal disease.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that affect how your body uses blood glucose. Diabetes can lead to periodontal disease, contribute to osteopenia through altered calcium metabolism, and affect nerve function, potentially influencing migratory pruritus.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine. Can cause osteopenia due to malabsorption, dental enamel defects, and has been linked with infertility.

diagnoses.name: Sjogren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that affects the glands that make moisture. It often comes with dry mouth, which can lead to severe oral pain and periodontal disease, and can be associated with systemic symptoms affecting fertility.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: A hormonal disorder causing enlarged ovaries with small cysts on the outer edges. It is a common cause of infertility in women and can be associated with insulin resistance, potentially linking it to conditions that affect oral health.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where the kidneys do not work effectively. It can result in mineral and bone disorder, leading to osteopenia, and is associated with a higher risk of periodontal disease.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) severely affects the immune system and can progress to Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome (AIDS). Can lead to various oral health problems including periodontal disease, has been associated with bone density loss, and can affect fertility.

diagnoses.name: Secondary Hyperparathyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition arising primarily due to vitamin D deficiency or chronic kidney disease, leading to increased parathyroid hormone levels. This can result in bone demineralization (osteopenia) and could potentially impact dental health.

diagnoses.name: Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory condition affecting skin and mucous membranes, including the oral cavity, potentially causing oral pain. It can also manifest on the skin as pruritic, purple lesions, possibly relating to migratory pruritus, though not directly connected to infertility or osteopenia.

diagnoses.name: Hepatitis C
diagnoses.description: A viral infection causing liver inflammation, sometimes leading to serious liver damage. It has been linked with extrahepatic manifestations including Sjogren's-like syndrome and mixed cryoglobulinemia, which can cause oral and dental health issues and has been associated with metabolic bone diseases.

diagnoses.name: Generalized Anxiety Disorder
diagnoses.reasoning: Anxiety and decreased appetite are common symptoms, and presyncope can occur in severe episodes.

diagnoses.name: Panic Disorder
diagnoses.reasoning: Panic attacks can lead to presyncope and anxiety; decreased appetite may also be present.

diagnoses.name: Brain Aneurysm
diagnoses.reasoning: Aneurysms in specific locations may pressure parts of the brain affecting eye movement (contributing to blepharospasm) and cause presyncope.

diagnoses.name: Hypoglycemia
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause anxiety, decreased appetite, and presyncope due to low blood sugar.

diagnoses.name: Benign Essential Blepharospasm
diagnoses.reasoning: Primary issue is blepharospasm, but stress and anxiety are known triggers; other symptoms could be stress-related.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.reasoning: May cause presyncope and anxiety; migraine is sometimes linked with aneurysms, and stress can trigger blepharospasm.

diagnoses.name: Pheochromocytoma
diagnoses.reasoning: A tumor of the adrenal gland that can cause anxiety, decreased appetite, and presyncope due to high adrenaline levels.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Increased metabolism might result in anxiety, decreased appetite, and presyncope; eye symptoms could be related.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Could potentially explain presyncope and blepharospasm due to nervous system damage; anxiety and decreased appetite may also be present.

diagnoses.name: Vasovagal Syncope
diagnoses.reasoning: Presyncope is a major symptom, and it can be triggered by anxiety; other symptoms might also occur in the context of a vasovagal response.

diagnoses.name: Viral Infection
diagnoses.reasoning: Many viral infections can cause a combination of diarrhea, muscle pain, and potentially exacerbate conditions like takotsubo cardiomyopathy due to stress on the body.

diagnoses.name: Bacterial Infection
diagnoses.reasoning: Certain bacterial infections could lead to dermatological symptoms like folliculitis, as well as gastrointestinal symptoms like diarrhea. Secondary effects could exacerbate or mimic cardiomyopathy symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Stress-Induced Cardiomyopathy
diagnoses.reasoning: Also known as takotsubo cardiomyopathy, this condition can be triggered by physical or emotional stress, potentially linked with the stress of illness.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Diseases
diagnoses.reasoning: Certain autoimmune conditions could potentially explain the wide range of symptoms, including muscle pain and skin conditions.

diagnoses.name: Staphylococcal Infections
diagnoses.reasoning: Staph infections can cause skin conditions such as folliculitis and also lead to systemic symptoms that could relate to the other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Though less common, Lyme disease can present with a variety of symptoms including muscle pain and dermatological manifestations. It can cause a wide range of cardiac and gastrointestinal issues as well.

diagnoses.name: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD)
diagnoses.reasoning: Conditions such as Crohn’s disease or Ulcerative Colitis could explain the gastrointestinal symptoms and may have systemic effects that could potentially relate to the other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.reasoning: Characterized primarily by muscle pain but also associated with a wide range of symptoms. It wouldn't directly cause takotsubo cardiomyopathy but could be related to the stress and pain levels.

diagnoses.name: Electrolyte Imbalance
diagnoses.reasoning: Severe diarrhea can lead to electrolyte imbalances, potentially affecting cardiac function and muscle pain. This imbalance could indirectly influence conditions like takotsubo cardiomyopathy.

diagnoses.name: Endocrine Disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: Disorders such as thyroid conditions could potentially explain a wide range of symptoms due to the hormonal imbalance affecting multiple body systems.

diagnoses: Toxin exposure (certain toxins may cause a combination of these symptoms)

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms including severe headaches, nausea, vomiting, difficulty speaking, numbness or tingling, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Tension-type headache
diagnoses.description: A common type of headache characterized by pain that is typically mild to moderate, bilateral, and feels like a tight band around the head.

diagnoses.name: Cluster headaches
diagnoses.description: A series of relatively short but extremely painful headaches every day for weeks or months at a time.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the protective membranes covering the brain and spinal cord, known collectively as the meninges. The inflammation may be caused by infection with viruses, bacteria, or other microorganisms.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: An uncommon type of stroke caused by bleeding into the space surrounding the brain. It can cause a sudden severe headache, stiff neck, vomiting, and light sensitivity.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic intracranial hypertension
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by high pressure inside the skull without any detectable reason. Symptoms may include headache, double vision, nausea, and pulsatile tinnitus.

diagnoses.name: Brain tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain or the skull vault. Brain tumors can be benign or malignant and can cause headaches, weakness, seizures, and problems with vision like scotoma.

diagnoses.name: Multiple sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves, resulting in a range of symptoms including fatigue, walking difficulties, and vision problems.

diagnoses.name: Optic neuritis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the optic nerve that can cause a partial or complete loss of vision, pain with eye movement, and sometimes, scotoma.

diagnoses.name: Pituitary adenoma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor of the pituitary gland that can cause a variety of symptoms, including vision changes, headache, and sometimes, symptoms related to hormonal imbalances or deficiencies.
